Bring a large #pot of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Roughly chop @peanuts{1/2%ounce}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating
whites from greens. Halve, core, and thinly slice @green bell pepper{1}.
Zest and quarter @lime{1}. Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce} to pot. Cook,
stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}. Drain and set aside.

While noodles cook, briefly heat a large dry pan over medium-high heat. Add
peanuts and cook, stirring occasionally, until golden and fragrant,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a plate. Wipe out pan.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in same pan over medium-high
heat. Add scallion whites, bell pepper, and half the @garlic powder{1%teaspoon};
season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Cook, stirring, until tender and lightly browned, ~{5-7%minutes}. Transfer
veggies to a plate. Reserve pan.

Add another drizzle of oil to same pan over medium-high heat. Add @ground
pork{10%ounce}; season with salt and pepper. Cook, undisturbed, until browned
on bottom, ~{3-4%minutes}. Break up into pieces; cook until cooked through,
~{2-4%minutes} more.

Stir in veggies, @sweet soy glaze{4%tablespoon}, @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce},
@butter{1%tablespoon}, and @Korean chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste. Cook,
stirring, until well coated, ~{1-2%minutes}; remove from heat.

> Rinse shrimp under cold water; pat dry with paper towels. Swap in shrimp (no
> need to break up into pieces!) or beef for pork.

Add drained noodles, a squeeze of lime juice, and a pinch of lime zest to pan;
toss to coat. Season with salt.

Divide noodle stir-fry between shallow #bowls.

Top with peanuts, scallion greens, and cilantro. Serve with remaining lime
wedges on the side.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.